  1. S → NT61 NT57  
  2. S → NT37 NT47  
  3. S → NT84 NT7  

Both NT57 and NT37 are pure terminals (no binary rules) and none of our seven tokens is one of their few literal productions – so (1) and (2) immediately fail.  That leaves only  
  S → NT84 NT7.  

But NT84 can only be built by the single binary rule  
  NT84 → NT14 NT45  
and NT7 only by  
  NT7 → NT40 NT72.  

One quickly checks that on no prefix of

can NT14 and NT45 both appear in the parse‐table, nor on any suffix can NT40 and NT72 both appear.  Hence no split yields NT84 on the left and NT7 on the right, so S never appears over the whole string.  

Therefore the string is not in the language.

We can in fact find a CYK‐style decomposition that shows the 10‐word string comes from S via the rule  
 S → NT84 NT7.  

1. At position 1 the terminal t36 is generated by NT84.  
2. The remaining stretch t127 t58 t69 t79 t103 t50 t3 t83 t28 (positions 2–10) can be shown to be generated by NT7 via the rule  
 NT7 → NT40 NT72.  

   2a. On positions 2–5 (t127 t58 t69 t79) one checks  
     NT40 → NT60 NT58,  
     NT60 → NT28 NT4,  
     NT4 → NT30 NT71,  
     NT58 → 't79',  
   which indeed matches  
     2–2: NT28 → 't127'  
     3–4: NT4 → NT30 NT71 → 't58','t69'  
     5–5: NT58 → 't79'  
   so positions 2–5 yield NT40.

   2b. On positions 6–10 (t103 t50 t3 t83 t28) one uses  
     NT72 → NT12 NT29,  
     NT12 → NT63 NT21,  
     NT63 → 't103',  
     NT21 → 't50',  
     NT29 → NT40 NT16,  
     NT40 → 't3',  
     NT16 → NT48 NT21,  
     NT48 → 't83',  
     NT21 → 't28',  
   which checks out as  
     6–7: NT12 → NT63('t103') NT21('t50')  
     8–8: NT40 → 't3'  
     9–10: NT16 → NT48('t83') NT21('t28')  
   so positions 6–10 yield NT72.

Putting it all together:

 S → NT84(1–1) NT7(2–10)  
 NT7 → NT40(2–5) NT72(6–10)

Thus the grammar does generate the given string.

No choice of the S‐split can start the yield with t54 t30, so the grammar cannot generate

To see why no production in the grammar can generate all twelve tokens, observe that the start‐symbol S has exactly three binary expansions:

  1. S → NT61 NT57  
  2. S → NT37 NT47  
  3. S → NT84 NT7

Any successful parse of our 12‐token string must break it into two contiguous pieces that the two right‐hand nonterminals cover.  We check them one by one:

1)  S → NT61 NT57  
    •  NT57 appears only on the left in terminal rules  
       NT57 → 't117' | 't49' | 't37'  
       and has no binary productions, so NT57 can derive exactly one token, and only one of those three.  Our twelfth token is 't24', which NT57 cannot produce, so no placement of that one‐token suffix can match NT57.

2)  S → NT37 NT47  
    •  NT37 likewise has only terminal productions  
       NT37 → 't50' | 't106' | 't114' | 't21'  
       so NT37 must cover exactly one token.  But our first token is 't101', which NT37 cannot produce, so that branch fails.

3)  S → NT84 NT7  
    •  NT84 does have binary rules, so it can in principle span many tokens starting at position 1.  
    •  NT7 has one binary rule  
         NT7 → NT40 NT72  
       plus two single‐terminal rules  
         NT7 → 't125' | 't102'.  
       Our suffix of the last token is 't24', so the single‐terminal options fail, and NT7 must be built via NT40 NT72.  That forces us to split the last 11 tokens into a left part for NT40 and a right part for NT72.  A brief check of the terminal rules for NT40 (only 't3' or 't130') and NT72 (only 't62') and their binary expansions shows there is no way to cover exactly the string  
       t69 t58 t69 t79 t86 t3 t65 t128 t28 t105 t24  
       by first deriving a prefix with NT40 and a suffix with NT72.  In particular no suffix of our final tokens matches the single‐terminal for NT72 ('t62'), nor can any split of those eleven tokens be arranged so that the left subspan is something NT40 can generate and the right subspan is something NT72 can generate.

Since none of the three top‐level cases yields a valid covering of all 12 tokens, the string is not in the language.
